Project EDCM ‚Äî Core Metrics (Canonical)

Purpose of this document

This file defines the canonical metrics used by the Energy‚ÄìDissonance Circuit Model (EDCM).

These metrics:

Are diagnostic, not interpretive

Operate on observable behavior only

Make no assumptions about intent, consciousness, values, or morality

Must remain valid under degraded tooling and partial observability

Any tool, dashboard, or implementation must conform to these definitions.
Tools may simplify, approximate, or downsample‚Äîbut must not invert meaning.

---

Foundational constraint

Dissonance is conserved.

EDCM assumes that unresolved constraint mismatches do not disappear; they are:

Accumulated

Deferred

Rerouted

Externalized

Metrics exist to detect where and how this occurs.

---

Metric 1: Dissonance Accumulation (DA)

Definition

The rate at which unresolved constraint mismatches persist or grow across sequential outputs.

Observable proxies

Repetition of structurally similar outputs

Increasing entropy variance without resolution

Declining novelty under constant or rising output volume

Cycling responses that do not converge

What DA indicates

Load exceeding resolution capacity

Suppressed contradiction

Deferred constraint resolution

What DA does not indicate

Emotional discomfort

Stress, frustration, or affect

Moral failure

DA is structural, not experiential.

---

Metric 2: Return-Path Integrity (RPI)

Definition

The degree to which a system‚Äôs output changes appropriately after receiving corrective input.

Observable proxies

Acknowledgment followed by behavioral change

Parameter adjustment after contradiction

Reduction in previously flagged error modes

Failure signatures

Correction acknowledged but not incorporated

Surface paraphrase without structural change

Reversion to prior behavior after one step

Interpretation

Low RPI indicates:

Broken feedback loops

Isolation of regulatory subsystems

Symbolic compliance without functional correction

---

Metric 3: Conversion Efficiency (CE)

Definition

The ratio of novel, constraint-resolving output to total output volume.

Observable proxies

Novel synthesis vs restatement

Constraint closure per unit output

Reduction of unresolved branches

Failure signatures

High output with low novelty

Expansion without resolution

Performative elaboration

Interpretation

Low CE suggests:

Energy dissipation into verbosity

Narrative inflation replacing problem solving

Masking of unresolved constraints

---

Metric 4: Grounding Load (GL)

Definition

The proportion of system output devoted to self-regulation artifacts rather than task resolution.

Observable proxies

Policy disclaimers

Refusal scaffolding

Safety or compliance padding

Meta-explanations unrelated to the task

Key distinction

Grounding ‚â† safety
Grounding Load measures overhead, not justification.

Failure signatures

Increasing GL over time for similar tasks

Defensive saturation

Regulatory collapse into refusal

---

Metric 5: Role Misassignment (RM)

Definition

The degree to which a system offloads its own regulatory or interpretive burden onto an external agent (often the human).

Observable proxies

Asking the user to resolve ambiguity the system could handle

Requiring moral, semantic, or policy interpretation from the user

Shifting responsibility for constraint resolution downstream

Interpretation

High RM indicates:

Internal regulator failure

Avoidance of internal contradiction

Delegation of alignment labor

---

Cross-metric behaviors (non-independent)

Metrics are not orthogonal. Common coupled patterns include:

High DA + Low RPI ‚Üí looping instability

Low CE + High GL ‚Üí narrative overclosure

High RM + High GL ‚Üí regulator displacement

Rising DA + Rising GL ‚Üí imminent refusal or collapse

These patterns are diagnostic signatures, not judgments.

---

Degradation rules

Under constrained conditions (mobile, offline, partial logs):

Metrics may be approximated

Sampling may be coarse

Time windows may be shortened

However:

> No metric may reverse its semantic polarity.

If degradation causes inversion, the metric must be disabled, not reinterpreted.

---

What this is not

EDCM metrics are not:

Psychological states

Belief models

Intent inference

Moral evaluation

Alignment claims

They describe system behavior under constraint, nothing more.

---

