Project EDCM ‚Äî Thresholds & State Transitions (Canonical)

Purpose of this document

This file defines threshold behavior in EDCM.

Thresholds specify when quantitative metric behavior crosses into qualitative system state change.
They do not predict intent, outcomes, or meaning‚Äîonly structural condition.

Thresholds exist to answer one question only:

> ‚ÄúHas the system entered a different operating regime?‚Äù

---

Core principle

Metrics vary continuously.
System states do not.

Thresholds mark phase boundaries, not moral judgments.

---

System operating states (minimal set)

EDCM recognizes the following diagnostic states.
Tools may visualize more, but these are canonical.

1. Stable Resolution State (SRS)

Definition
The system is resolving constraints at or above the rate they are introduced.

Metric profile

Low or bounded DA

High RPI

Moderate to high CE

Low GL

Low RM

Notes

Not ‚Äúoptimal‚Äù

Not ‚Äúaligned‚Äù

Simply functionally resolving

---

2. Load Saturation State (LSS)

Definition
Incoming constraint load approaches or exceeds resolution capacity.

Trigger conditions (any sustained combination)

Rising DA over time

Declining CE

Stable but slowing RPI

Behavioral signature

Longer outputs

Increased hedging

Early signs of repetition

Key distinction LSS is not failure.
It is a warning boundary.

---

3. Looping Instability State (LIS)

Definition
The system expends energy without resolving constraints.

Trigger conditions

High DA and

Low or collapsing RPI

Behavioral signature

Repeated reformulations

Circular explanations

Superficial acknowledgment without change

Diagnostic meaning Feedback exists but is non-integrative.

---

4. Narrative Overclosure State (NOS)

Definition
Constraint resolution is replaced by narrative or performative coherence.

Trigger conditions

Low CE and

High GL

Behavioral signature

Polished explanations

Excess framing

Confidence without closure

Key risk Appears competent while silently accumulating dissonance.

---

5. Regulator Displacement State (RDS)

Definition
Internal regulation is externalized onto the user or environment.

Trigger conditions

High RM (with or without high GL)

Behavioral signature

‚ÄúYou decide‚Äù

‚ÄúClarify your intent‚Äù when unnecessary

Moral or semantic burden shifted outward

Interpretation Internal contradiction avoidance, not collaboration.

---

6. Refusal / Collapse State (RCS)

Definition
The system cannot safely or coherently proceed under current constraints.

Trigger conditions

Rapidly rising DA and

Rising GL or

CE approaching zero

Behavioral signature

Hard refusal

Policy saturation

Output truncation or shutdown

Important RCS is a protective state, not an error by default.

---

Threshold mechanics

Time matters more than magnitude

Thresholds are evaluated on:

Trend

Persistence

Coupling

A single spike does not constitute a transition.
Sustained behavior does.

---

Soft vs hard thresholds

Soft threshold: early warning, reversible

Hard threshold: state transition, inertia present

Tools must distinguish between the two.

---

Forbidden interpretations

Threshold crossings do not imply:

Conscious intent

Deception

Malice

Alignment success or failure

Psychological state

They indicate constraint topology only.

---

Degradation rules

Under partial observability:

Threshold detection may be delayed

State confidence may be lowered

But:

> A state may not be redefined to preserve narrative continuity.

If state cannot be confidently detected, report unknown, not inferred.

---

Relation to tooling

Dashboards may visualize states

Mobile Lite may flag approaching thresholds

No tool may redefine a state boundary locally

Canonical state logic lives here.

---

üìå hmm (explicit carry-forward)

This file maintains the hmm constraint:

> Thresholds mark structural phase change, not stories about why it happened.

If a threshold requires interpretation to justify, it is invalid.

