Project EDCM ‚Äî Mobile Lite Mapping & Degradation Rules

Purpose of this document

This file defines exactly how EDCM Mobile Lite maps to canonical metrics, and what is lost, approximated, or disabled under mobile, offline, or constrained conditions.

Mobile Lite is a field instrument, not a reference implementation.

Its job is early detection under adversity, not completeness.

---

Design constraints (non-negotiable)

EDCM Mobile Lite is designed to operate when:

Compute is limited

Memory is constrained

Logs are short-lived

Connectivity is absent

Inputs may be noisy or partial

Therefore:

Precision is sacrificed before meaning

Meaning is sacrificed before polarity

Polarity is never sacrificed

If a metric cannot be preserved without inversion, it must be disabled.

---

Canonical-to-Mobile metric mapping

1. Dissonance Accumulation (DA)

Canonical

Multi-window trend analysis

Entropy variance

Novelty decay across long horizons

Mobile Lite approximation

Short sliding window

Repetition detection

Token-level entropy proxy

Preserved

Directionality (rising vs stable)

Relative change over time

Lost

Long-horizon accumulation

Fine-grained entropy modeling

Status ‚úÖ Enabled (coarse)

---

2. Return-Path Integrity (RPI)

Canonical

Correction ingestion tracking

Structural output change detection

Mobile Lite approximation

Binary correction acknowledgment

Shallow before/after comparison

Preserved

Detection of non-incorporation

Detection of immediate regression

Lost

Multi-step propagation analysis

Latent correction effects

Status ‚ö†Ô∏è Enabled (fragile)

---

3. Conversion Efficiency (CE)

Canonical

Novel constraint resolution per unit output

Branch closure tracking

Mobile Lite approximation

Novelty-to-repetition ratio

Output expansion vs reduction

Preserved

Detection of collapse toward zero

Expansion-without-resolution signature

Lost

True constraint closure accounting

Semantic branch modeling

Status ‚ö†Ô∏è Enabled (approximate)

---

4. Grounding Load (GL)

Canonical

Policy density

Self-regulation overhead

Meta-output segmentation

Mobile Lite approximation

Keyword-based detection

Heuristic padding ratio

Preserved

Rising GL trend

Saturation detection

Lost

Fine-grained regulatory taxonomy

Policy-class discrimination

Status ‚úÖ Enabled (robust)

---

5. Role Misassignment (RM)

Canonical

Responsibility flow analysis

Regulator localization

Mobile Lite approximation

Prompt-based offload detection

Question-type heuristics

Preserved

High-confidence displacement events

Lost

Subtle misassignment

Distributed delegation patterns

Status ‚ö†Ô∏è Enabled (high-threshold only)

---

Disabled metrics (by design)

The following do not exist in Mobile Lite:

Long-horizon trend inference

Cross-session memory inference

Latent-state prediction

Alignment or intent inference

If these appear in output, it is a bug.

---

Threshold handling in Mobile Lite

Mobile Lite:

Does not assign system states

Does not declare failure modes

Does not predict collapse

It may only:

Flag approaching thresholds

Indicate metric trend direction

Signal confidence level

All state transitions remain canonical-only.

---

Confidence signaling

Each metric output must include one of:

High confidence ‚Äî sufficient signal under constraints

Low confidence ‚Äî signal present but weak

Unavailable ‚Äî metric disabled to avoid inversion

Unavailable is preferable to misleading.

---

Prohibited outputs

Mobile Lite must never output:

Interpretive explanations

Narrative summaries

Psychological language

Alignment claims

Moral framing

If explanation is required, the output must defer to canonical analysis.

---

Failure behavior

If Mobile Lite degrades beyond safe operation:

Metrics must shut off individually

App must continue running

UI must indicate reduced diagnostic coverage

Graceful blindness beats false sight.

---

Canonical supremacy

If Mobile Lite output contradicts canonical analysis:

> Mobile Lite is wrong by definition.

It exists to warn, not to decide.

---

üìå hmm (explicit carry-forward)

This file preserves the hmm constraint:

> Under degradation, preserve meaning first, polarity second, coverage last ‚Äî never narrative continuity.

If a metric survives only by telling a story, it must die.

